obo:ECO_0006052  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_2907  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.3: \"PACSIN1 knockdown reduces NMDA-induced GluA2 internalization\"\n- \"These data indicate that PACSIN1 may not regulate AMPAR trafficking under basal conditions.\"\n- \" the amount of internalized myc-GluA2 was significantly reduced in PACSIN1 knockdown neurons compared with control neurons (internalization index, pSuper, 1 ± 0.04; sh#1, 0.68 ± 0.03) (Fig. 3 E and F). The reduction in NMDA-induced myc-GluA2 internalization caused by PACSIN1 shRNA could be fully rescued by the expression of an shRNA-resistant PACSIN1 rescue construct in the hippocampal neurons (0.92 ± 0.05) (Fig. 3 E and F). \"\n\nFig.4: \"PICK1 binding to the PACSIN1-variable region is required for activity-dependent GluA2 internalization\"\n- \"there was a significant decrease in intracellular myc-GluA2 following NMDA stimulation in neurons that were transfected with HA-PACSIN1 tmE, which had reduced binding with PICK1 (0.84 ± 0.03) (Fig. 4 D and E).\". Experimental description: - \"Cultured neurons were prepared from E18 rat pups as described previously (44).\"\n- Species of over-expressed PACSIN1 is not stated in the publication. The authors were contacted for additional information (dd 16/3/2018, Victor Anggono [v.anggono@uq.edu.au]). Answer: \"\n\nDear Pim,\nThe PACSIN1 cDNA that we used in the PNAS paper is of murine (mouse) origin.\nIf you require further information, please do not hesitate to contact me directly.\nBest wishes,\nVictor\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0593-3443" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2018-03-17" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_2907" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

